LLM is the general category — Claude and ChatGPT are specific examples of LLMs, built by different companies.

Think of it like this:

• LLM (Large Language Model)
  = the general technology/category. It's a type of AI
    model trained on huge amounts of text to understand and generate language.

• Claude
  = an LLM made by Anthropic.

• ChatGPT
  = not actually the LLM itself — it's the chat product/interface built on top of
    an LLM called GPT (made by OpenAI). So "GPT-4" is the LLM, "ChatGPT" is the app
    you talk to it through.

• Other LLMs:
  Google's Gemini, Meta's Llama, Mistral's models, etc.
-----------------------------------------------------------------
we can create custom ai using llm right?

Yes, exactly — that's essentially what "building on an LLM" means. You don't train a model from scratch (that requires massive 
compute/data most companies don't have); instead you build a custom AI application on top of an existing LLM like Claude or GPT, 
using its API.

What "custom" actually means in practice:

1. System prompt / instructions
   — you tell the LLM its role, tone, constraints (e.g., "you
   are a Kubernetes troubleshooting assistant for our EKS
   clusters, only suggest read-only diagnostics unless
   explicitly asked to remediate").

2. Tool/function calling
   — you give it specific tools it can call:
     get_pod_logs(),
     check_argocd_sync_status(),
     run_terraform_plan().
   The LLM decides when to call them based on the
   conversation; your code executes the actual logic.

3. RAG (Retrieval-Augmented Generation)
   — you feed it your own data (runbooks, past incident
   reports, your Terraform module docs) so it answers using
   your context, not just its general training.

4. Fine-tuning (less common, more effort)
   — actually adjusting the model's weights on your own
   examples. Usually unnecessary — prompting + tools + RAG
   covers most custom use cases.

Concretely, for your setup:

You could build a custom AI assistant that's "Claude, but
scoped to your infra" — it knows your EKS topology, can
query ArgoCD/CloudWatch via tools, and only speaks in the
context of your Akamai/NLB/NGINX Ingress stack. That's not
a new LLM — it's Claude (or any LLM) wrapped with your
prompt, your tools, and your data.

This is the standard path almost every "custom AI" product
you see today takes — nobody's training a foundation model
per use case; they're all layering on top of a handful of
base LLMs (Claude, GPT, Gemini, Llama).

